Kate Bedingfield, who has served as White House Communications Director since President Biden's inauguration, will leave the White House at the end of February. She will be replaced by Ben LaBolt. Bedingfield has played a significant role in the successes of the first two years of the Biden-Harris Administration. She previously held various communications leadership roles during the Obama-Biden Administration and has worked in communications for the Motion Picture Association of America and Monumental Sports and Entertainment. LaBolt has worked with President Biden in this administration and during the Obama-Biden years. He has experience in presidential campaigns and congressional communications roles. He currently leads a communications and marketing agency. LaBolt is making history as the first openly gay White House communications director. President Biden praised Bedingfield for her loyalty and trusted advice and expressed confidence in LaBolt's abilities to fill her shoes.